          "body": "The second scene (41:4-9) compounds the first. Eighty men approach from Shechem, Shiloh, and Samaria — cities of the former northern kingdom — bearing grain offerings and incense for the house of the Lord (41:5). Their shaved beards, torn garments, and gashed bodies mark them as mourners: they have heard of Jerusalem's fall and are enacting the rituals of corporate grief prescribed in passages like Lamentations and Joel 2:12-13. They are, in other words, among the most theologically oriented people left in the land — seeking God even in the ruins. Ishmael meets them weeping (41:6), weaponizing grief as deception, and leads them into the city where his men slaughter seventy of them. Ten survive by offering stored grain and oil (41:8). The narrator then delivers one of the chapter's most haunting details: the cistern Ishmael uses as a mass grave is the one King Asa built two centuries earlier as a military fortification against Baasha of Israel (41:9). A structure built to protect the kingdom now holds its victims. The pilgrims who sought the house of the Lord find instead a cistern of the slain."
