          "title": "The rescue at Gibeon — incomplete justice",
          "body": "Johanan's pursuit (41:11-15) provides the chapter's only movement toward justice, but the resolution is partial. He intercepts Ishmael at the great pool of Gibeon — an archaeologically confirmed water installation and the site of one of Israel's famous judicial combats (2 Sam. 2:13-17). When the captives see Johanan and the commanders, they are *glad* (41:13, *samach*) — one of the few positive emotional notes in the chapter — and turn back voluntarily (41:14). The people themselves recognize the difference between captivity under a murderer and rescue under a commander. But Ishmael escapes with eight men to Ammon (41:15). The perpetrator of Gedaliah's assassination, the slaughter of seventy pilgrims, and the captivity of the remnant faces no earthly justice in the chapter. The narrative's refusal to provide closure here is not an oversight; it is a theological statement about the incompleteness of human reckoning. Vengeance belongs to the Lord (Deut. 32:35; Jer. 51:56), and the narrator will not manufacture a resolution the text does not provide."
